result.execSummary:
The defendant Vaughn P. Dailey was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Repeater], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

case called at 11:15am.
Defendant Vaughn P. Dailey appear from Jackson Correctional Institution, in custody.  Attorney Jeffrey De La Rosa appears. ADA Krysta Parson appears. 
The Court finds the video-connection sight and sound sufficient. 
The Court verifies with Mr. Dailey that he understands he has the right to be present in the courtroom for sentencing, and he is waiving this right. 
Service of the Amended Information, reading waived, the charges and maximum penalties are recited.
Constitutional rights reviewed; elements are recited; plea of " Guilty " entered on Count #2; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified.  The Court accepts the plea, finds the Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads in and dismisses Count #1. 

On Count #2 the Court sentences Mr. Dailey to:
--serve 12 months in Jail concurrent to any other sentence in being, to commence forthwith
--0 days credit for time already served given
--pay costs and surcharge; this amount is to be converted to a civil judgment 
The Court finds that the Defendant is not free to request expungement of this case.

The Defendant verifies that the date of birth listed on the Criminal Complaint is correct. 
Service of Complaint admitted, reading waived, the charges and maximum penalties are recited.
Preliminary Hearing time limit is waived by both parties.
The Court finds probable cause to exist on the four corners of the Criminal Compliant

The Court requires a $1,500.00 Signature Bond with conditions:
--maintain absolute sobriety
--no possession or consumption of alcohol
--no presence in bars, taverns, liquor stores
--no contact with Victim 1 or Victim 1's mother
--no presence at Victim 1's residence
--no acts or threats of violence toward any person
--submit to the booking process prior to being released from the Jefferson County Jail, if it has not been done so already
